## Refactor proposal for `src/Card.tsx`

The fixture is intentionally messy (it exists to keep these three detectors honest), so I'll leave the file alone and show what the corrected version should look like instead.

### Change 1 — fix `accessible_interaction_risk` (crime_00001)

The outer `<div onClick>` is non-reachable by keyboard and invisible to screen readers. Either make it a real button or, if the card needs to remain a `<div>` for layout, attach `role`, `tabIndex`, an accessible label, and a keyboard handler.

```tsx
// Was: <div onClick={() => console.log("clicked")}>
<button type="button" onClick={handleClick} className="card">
  …
</button>
```

If the card must stay a `<div>` (e.g. it contains nested interactives), the minimum bar is:

```tsx
<div
  role="button"
  tabIndex={0}
  aria-label="Open card"
  onClick={handleClick}
  onKeyDown={(e) => (e.key === "Enter" || e.key === " ") && handleClick()}
>
```

### Change 2 — fix `design_token_escape` (crime_00002)

All nine raw literals (`#ff00aa`, `#0a0a0a`, `#cccccc`, `#1a73e8`, `rgb(0,0,0)`, plus the shadow and the secondary hex colors on lines 24/27) move into the design system. Replace inline `style` with semantic class names (or a styled-component) backed by tokens:

```tsx
// Card.module.css (or whatever the project's convention is)
.card {
  background: var(--color-surface-accent);
  color:      var(--color-foreground);
  border:     1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
  outline-color: var(--color-focus-ring);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-card);
  padding:    var(--space-6);
  border-radius: var(--radius-md);
}
.card__body    { color: var(--color-foreground-muted); }
.card__sidebar { color: var(--color-foreground-subtle); }
```

```tsx
<button type="button" className="card" onClick={handleClick}>
  <div className="card__body">{children}</div>
  <div className="card__sidebar">sidebar</div>
</button>
```

Every literal that came from the inline `style` block now points at a token; agents extending this file can't accidentally fork the palette.

### Change 3 — fix `responsive_fragility` (crime_00003)

The three offenders are `width: 800`, `width: 720`, and `fontSize: 18` with no `@media` in the file. Swap fixed widths for `max-width` + fluid width, and use `clamp()`/`rem` for typography. Then add a media query so the two columns stack on small viewports.

```css
.card {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 50rem;          /* was width: 800px */
  font-size: clamp(1rem, 1vw + 0.85rem, 1.125rem); /* was 18px */
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 15rem;
  gap: var(--space-4);
}
.card__body    { min-width: 0; }     /* was width: 720px */
.card__sidebar { width: 100%; }      /* was width: 240px */

@media (max-width: 40rem) {
  .card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } /* sidebar drops below body */
}
```

### How the three changes map back to the findings

| Finding | Change | Why it clears the detector |
|---|---|---|
| `accessible_interaction_risk` (crime_00001) | Outer element becomes a `<button>` (or `<div>` gains `role`, `tabIndex`, `aria-label`, `onKeyDown`) | No more clickable non-button without a11y metadata |
| `design_token_escape` (crime_00002) | All 9 raw color/px/rgb/shadow literals replaced by `var(--…)` tokens in a CSS module | No hard-coded style values left in JSX |
| `responsive_fragility` (crime_00003) | Fixed widths → `max-width` + `100%`; `18px` → `clamp()`; file gains an `@media` rule | No bare fixed widths; media query present |

I haven't edited the fixture — it's load-bearing for the detector evals. If you want me to apply this to a real file, point me at it.
